SIMPLE: junction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Junction
<hw>Junc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>junctio</ets>, fr. <ets>jungere</ets>, <ets>junctum</ets>, to join:
cf. F. <ets>jonction</ets>. See <er>Join</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of joining, or the state of being joined;
union; combination; coalition; <as>as, the <ex>junction</ex> of two
armies or detachments; the <ex>junction</ex> of paths.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The place or point of union, meeting, or junction;
specifically, the place where two or more lines of railway meet or
cross.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Junction plate</b></col> <fld>(Boilers)</fld>, <cd>a
covering or break-join plate riveted to and uniting the edges of sheets
which make a butt joint.</cd> -- <col><b>Junction rails</b></col>
<fld>(Railroads)</fld>, <cd>the switch, or movable, rails, connecting
one line of track with another.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Junction box</ent>⟦br⟧
